1 3. The director or the director's designee shall serve as chairman of the board and is an
2 ex officio member of the board.
3 4. The committee shall:
4 a. Recommend standards and procedures relating to l icensing, permitting, and
5 inspections of sewer, septic, and private water systems, including a requirement
6 for proposed inspections to be completed within one business day.
7 b. Create and recommend a statewide technical guide for sewer, septic, and private
8 water systems.
9 Environmental quality advisory committee - Members - Terms of office - Vacancies.
10 Each appointed member of the committee shall qualify by taking the oath of office required
11 of civil officers and shall hold office for a term of four years and until a successor is appointed
12 and qualified. The terms of office of the appointed members must be arranged so no more than
13 two terms expire on June thirtieth of each year. To accomplish the staggering, the initial term of
14 appointees may be for less than four years. The governor shall fill a vacancy on the board by
15 appointment from the class of members to which the member belonged.
16 Certain septic, sewer, and private water systems exempt.
17 This chapter does not apply to any septic, sewer, or private water system constructed,
18 produced, or installed before August 1, 2025, or the extension of such a system.
19 SECTION 2. REPEAL. Sections 23-35-02.2 and 23-35-02.3 of the North Dakota Century
20 Code are repealed.
21 SECTION 3. TRANSFER - FUNDS UNDER THE CONTROL OF THE STATE BOARD OF
22 PLUMBING TO DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY - SEPTIC SYSTEMS. The
23 state board of plumbing shall transfer any remaining funds at the end of the biennium, from the
24 state plumbing board fund relating to the regulation of septic tanks and septic systems, to the
25 department of environmental quality operating fund for the purpose of the regulation of septic
26 tanks and septic systems.
